{"key":"post-20099290","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>20099290</id>\n<content>&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/facepalm.gif&quot; alt=&quot;:facepalm:&quot; title=&quot;:facepalm:&quot;/&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Thicker filters have &lt;b&gt;LESS&lt;/b&gt; resistance than thinner ones.&amp;nbsp; I've typed that at least 1000 times over the years and it's on every spec sheet.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Choose a filter with sufficient resistance to achieve laminar flow.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Most flowhood filters are 5&quot; to 7&quot; in thickness.&amp;nbsp; They have high resistance, but less debris holding capacity.&amp;nbsp; This is why we use prefilters.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Clean room filters (not what you want) are thicker at 12&quot; to 15&quot; so they have more debris holding capacity, but a lower resistance to provide higher flow rates to clean entire rooms.&amp;nbsp; These are not recommended for flow hoods.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>20099357</next>\n<prev>20099253</prev>\n<first>20098878</first>\n<last>20102482</last>\n<when>1402231630</when>\n<utime>06/08/14 03:47 PM</utime>\n</post>"}